From: Andrew Patrick Budziszek
Sent: Sunday, September 07, 2014 1:43 AM
To: James Earl Edwards II; Tommy Robert Domenico; Joseph Paul Thomaschaske III; Andrew Patrick Budziszek
Subject: Version Control and other notes
 
Hey, guys.

Version control is set up and has been tested on IntelliJ. IntelliJ Community Edition is free and can be downloaded from JetBrain's website mentioned in an earlier e-mail. I highly recommend IntelliJ as it is a more modern Java IDE with a visual pleasing interface that is starting to be used by many developers today in place of Eclipse. It also offers great Smart Code completion that makes sure you are writing optimized code. 

I tested the creation of a project, pushing changes of a project, and getting the latest version(updating) of the project. These functions were tested using a Windows Azure Virtual Machine. All of these functions appear to be working.

Here is our GitHub's login information if you would like to try it in the IDE of your choice:
Username: VelvetMastermind
Password: VelvetMastermind14
Project Name: VelvetMastermind

In IntelliJ our project can be easily accessed:
Open any project. (This is just so we can get to VCS).
In the VCS tab go down to "Checkout from Version Control" and select "GitHub".
Here you will enter the GitHub login information shown above. 
Enter the login info and select our project. If you are prompted to enter a master password, type in "VelvetMastermind14". 
Now IntelliJ should pull the project from GitHub. 
Select to Open the project in a New Window. 
You should now have the project. 
Navigate to the 'src' folder and make some changes to the "TestMastermindDriver" class. (Comments are fine)
After making changes go to VCS and commit/push your changes. Send out an email when you've done so. 

If you use an IDE other than IntelliJ, please test it to make sure you can import the project, commit/push changes, and get the latest version(update) our project. Testing of version control should be done by Wednesday, September 9th so we don't have to worry about it in the future. Send an email out with the IDE you are using and whether or not you successfully accessed the project. If you have any problems we can try our best to make sure everyone is able to access and change the project as needed.

We'll work out any final kinks in our meeting this Friday @ 6PM. I'll try reserving a room in the library for that night.

A final note:​ When replying to e-mails, sending 'OK' to only the sender is fine. It's counterproductive to send that sort of reply to the entire group. Only 'reply all' if you are adding/suggesting something to the original e-mail that had been sent out.

Thanks.

Andrew Budziszek
UW-Milwaukee
College of Engineering and Applied Science
Computer Science
